(AP Photo/LucasFilm, Disney) Photo: Courtesy Photo 'Star Wars' prompts ticket highs, trailer lows 1 / 3 Back to Gallery It's been a rocky several hours for fans eager for the December opening of "Star Wars: Episode VII -The Force Awakens," the seventh film in the franchise's history.
Advance tickets went on sale Monday night, after the latest trailer made its debut on ESPN during "Monday Night Football," mostly to rapturous fan acclaim. But demand crashed such popular buying sites as Fandango, Alamo Draft House and AMC.
Meanwhile, some disgruntled fans on Twitter -- the Jar Jar Binks fan club? -- blasted the movie as anti-white.
Scalpers on eBay were attempting to sell tickets for $1,000.
As of Tuesday afternoon, only one screen in Houston for December 17, the first evening it will be showing, at Edwards Marq'E theater, appeared to be sold out.
The movie is expected to make $100 million in North America on its first weekend and go on to become one of the highest-grossing movies in history.
